{
  "decision_summary": "The chip temperature (89.26°C) exceeds the limit (85.0°C). The previous attempt to increase spreader conductivity to 700 failed due to the upper bound of 500. Since the spreader material is already at its maximum conductivity (500 W/(m*K)), the next most effective lever is to increase the geometric cross-section of the heat spreader to improve lateral heat distribution. I will increase the spreader width by 20% (from 0.7 to 0.84), which is within the allowed 1.5x step ratio and fits within the design domain bounds.",
  "changes": [
    {
      "path": "components.2.width",
      "action": "set",
      "old": 0.7,
      "new": 0.84,
      "reason": "Increasing the heat spreader width expands the area available for lateral heat conduction, reducing thermal resistance and lowering the peak chip temperature. This is the primary available lever since material conductivity is already maximized."
    }
  ],
  "expected_effects": [
    "Reduced thermal resistance in the spreader layer",
    "Lower peak temperature in the chip component",
    "Improved feasibility regarding the chip_max_temperature constraint"
  ],
  "risk_notes": [
    "Widening the spreader brings it closer to the left/right domain boundaries; ensure it does not exceed the design domain width of 1.2m (current x0=0.25, new width 0.84 -> x1=1.09, which is safe).",
    "If this geometric change is insufficient, subsequent steps may need to explore increasing base plate conductivity or adjusting boundary conditions if permissible."
  ]
}
